This paper is about natural language processing and dependency parsing, which are both subfields of computer science. The paper specifically focuses on the Stanford typed dependencies, which are commonly used in computational linguistics and natural language processing. Therefore, the most likely sub-category is cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also discusses statistical dependency parsing algorithms, which fall under machine learning and artificial intelligence, making cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) likely sub-categories as well. Additionally, the paper explores the effects of input representations, which could fall under neural networks and computational neuroscience (cs.NE) or information retrieval (cs.IR).
